To ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of Supplies and Materials, we recommended that the LCE require:

The Property Officer to maintain perpetual inventory records of Supplies and Materials purchased and to ensure that complete records of the items issued to requisitioning departments/offices are kept. At the end of each month, he shall prepare the monthly Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued, a copy of which shall be furnished the Municipal Accountant for recording;

The Municipal Accountant to record all regular purchases of Supplies and Materials under the proper inventory account following the perpetual inventory method;

At the end of each semester, the Property Officer shall conduct an inventory, in coordination with the concerned department/office, of all unused Supplies and Materials and shall prepare a consolidated report thereon and furnish the Municipal Accountant a copy thereof; and

The Municipal Accountant to take up the necessary adjustment, if any, in the respective inventory and expense accounts for Supplies and Materials based on the consolidated inventory report provided by the Property Officer

We recommended that the Management:
Require the General Services Officer (GSO) to prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) based on the Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS), at least on a monthly basis, to be submitted to the Municipal Accountant as basis for the preparation of the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record issuances of inventories from stock;
Further, the GSO prepare and maintain stock cards for each type of inventory, with complete information/data to facilitate verification receipts, issuances and balances of inventories on hand;
Require the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records, at least, on a quarterly basis to ensure accuracy of the balances of the inventory accounts;
Provide an adequate stockroom to safely keep all procured stocks of the LGU so that inventories are only issued to end-users when needed; and
Subject to availability of funds, augment the manpower of the GSO so that there will be personnel charged with the recording, monitoring, and safekeeping of the inventories of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management require:
The General Services Officer (GSO) to conduct the annual physical count of the Municipality’s PPE at the end of each year and to prepare the corresponding inventory report thereon, copy furnished the Auditor;
The Municipal Accountant and the GSO to maintain complete, accurate and updated PPE Ledgers and Property Cards, respectively;
For both officers to reconcile the results of the physical inventory with the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards maintained by the Property and Accounting Units, respectively, and effect the necessary adjustments for deficiencies noted.
We also recommended that management create an inventory committee that will focus on completing the inventory taking and identify non-existing/missing PPE. Thereafter, to follow the procedures and guidelines set forth in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, for proper disposition of non-existing/missing PPE.

We recommended that:
The BAC Members thoroughly examine the submitted bidding documents by the bidders as required under Sections 23.5.1.3 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184, as well as take into account COA Circular 2012-003 in order for them to determine if the bidders are eligible to bid for procurement of IT Broadcasting and Telecommunications equipment, and;
The Management submit a valid comment and justification for our evaluation, as to why the transaction should not be disallowed in violation of RA 9184

We recommended that the Management:
Observe the pertinent rules and regulations of the aforecited regulation to ensure the propriety of transaction;
Ensure proper documentation of recipients of supplies distribution;
Conduct future distribution activities in an efficient and prudent manner; and
Submit a valid comment and justification for our evaluation, as to why the transaction should not be disallowed in violation of COA Circular 2012-003.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
to conduct risk assessment;
to identify critical processes and functions;
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
Further, we recommended that members of the working group be capacitated by allowing them to attend seminars/trainings on the formulation of the PSCP.

We recommended the following courses of action:

The Accounting Office ensure that a Relief distribution sheet (RDS) be attached as part of the supporting documents for disbursements relating to the procurement of relief goods for distribution under the Bayanihan Grant;

The barangays under the jurisdiction of the Municipality shall constantly update its database for its registered residents and their complete address to facilitate verification of the accomplished distribution lists;

The distribution list shall bear in the heading of each page: a) proper title of the activity; b) barangay name and purok; c) date of distribution; d) specific details of the goods per pack distributed; e) proper accounting or numbering of the recipients;

The implementing unit of the Municipality or in-charge of the distribution shall ensure that all recipients named in the distribution list affix their signature to signify that goods were received by them.

We recommended that Management: 

Pursue the immediate approval of the Ten-Year ESWMP as required under R.A. No. 9003 to ensure its sustainability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international progress in the area of Solid Waste Management;

Properly supervise the maintenance of all Material Recovery Facilities in all the Barangays of the Municipality to achieve its purpose of ensuring the cleanliness of the entire community.

We recommended that Management:

Enforce the payment of liquidated damages against erring contractors for non-performance of their obligations to the LGU within the periods stipulated in the contracts;

Strictly adhere to the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its Revised IRR and other existing regulations and practices relative to the preparation of project plans and programs to avoid suspensions or disallowances in audit;

Require the MPDO and the MEO to monitor the implementation of the various PPAs to ensure the timely completion thereof in order to achieve the desired outcomes which are essential in the attainment of its goals and objectives in improving the quality of life of its constituents; and

Adopt strategies, despite personnel limitations, so that planned projects by the LGU may be timely implemented within the budget year and completed within the stipulated time frames.

